Chapter forty-six on cauterizing the uvula.	CHAPTER FORTY-SIX. On cauterization for contusion.	0.7542318
If pain occurs in some organs due to a fall or a blow, and that pain lasts for a long time, and treatment with medications is not effective	When pain occurs in some limb due to a fall or a blow and the pain becomes chronic and medical treatment has no effect upon it, you should cauterize it with the punctate cautery.	0.73153573
then it should be cauterized with a point cautery, and the cauterization of each organ should be according to its size, smallness, weakness, strength, and the severity and chronicity of the pain.	In each case the cauterization should be in proportion to the size of the limb, its strength or weakness, and the chronicity of the pain and contusion in it.	0.7111051
If it heals from the first cauterization, then fine, otherwise, repeat the cauterization because it is the nature of these pains to move from the organ to what is near it. Therefore, it is necessary to follow it with cauterization until the patient recovers.	If it is cured at the first cauterization, good; otherwise repeat the cauterization. For it is customary for these pains to move from one part to a neighbouring part, and you must follow them with the cautery till the patient is cured.	0.87644917
